Overview¶

In this notebook we will download and work with several interest rates from Bundesbank.

Following things are part of the analysis:

  • how to download data
  • daily and monthly data: how far do they go back?
  • there are different symbols for similar interest rates (e.g. 5 year interest rates). Are there any differences?
  • each symbol could be downloaded in different currencies. Is there a difference? EUR vs DEM?

Eventually we are interested not in interest rates, but in bond indices: investments into bonds that get rolled over.

  • which bond indices are directly available?
  • how can we construct synthetic bond indices from interest rates?

Available data

List of indices at Bundesbank:

https://www.bundesbank.de/dynamic/action/en/statistics/time-series-databases/time-series-databases/759784/759784?listId=www_skms_mb05

List of interest rates and yields:

https://www.bundesbank.de/en/statistics/money-and-capital-markets/interest-rates-and-yields/daily-term-structure-on-listed-federal-securities-651570

Description of download parameters:

https://www.bundesbank.de/en/statistics/statistics/time-series-databases-750894#tar-9

Bond indices¶

Two bond indices exist for data download at Bundesbank:

  • BBK01.WU046A: REX performance index / End 1987 = 100 / End of month
  • BBK01.WX9141: iBoxx EUR Germany performance index / End 1998 = 100 / End of month

Conclusion:

  • both are quite similar to each other, but REXP is available much longer (before 1969)
  • both series are monthly data

REXP description:

Der REX-Performance-Index (REXP) der Deutsche Börse AG ist der zum Anleiheportefeuille des Deutschen Rentenindex (REX) passende Performanceindex. Er gibt die Wertentwicklung des REX-Portfolios an, in das die Kuponzahlungen unter Beibehaltung der Portfoliostruktur reinvestiert werden.

Different currencies¶

For each time series one can choose between two different currency specifications:

  • default
  • hypothetical

In theory it is not fully obvious which currency one should expect for historic bond index values before the introduction of the Euro. These values could either be denominated in DEM or in synthetically backward computed values for EUR.

Conclusion:

  • as both default and hypothetical values lead to equal results, currency before 1999 needs to be DEM

Synthetic bond index values from interest rates¶

Interest rates themselves are not an investable asset, but one would need to invest into bonds and roll them over. So we will now derive synthetic bond index values from historic interest rates and compare them to the historic price path that we have for REXP.

1st method: compounding only, no bond price moves¶

Proxy of compounding with one-month rolling. As proxy we treat the respective interest rate as constant and ignore any price moves that are introduced by interest rate changes. This eliminates a substantial risk component of bonds and will result in time series that are monotonically increasing.

In [23]:
proxy_idx = ((int_rates_monthly.dropna() / 100 / 12) + 1).cumprod()
rexp_and_proxy = rexp.join(proxy_idx, how='inner')
rexp_and_proxy = rexp_and_proxy / rexp_and_proxy.iloc[0, :]
rexp_and_proxy.plot()

2nd method: incorporating bond price fluctuations¶

A more sophisticated approximation method is to derive compouding from rolling zero coupon bonds with approximated prices.

With 8-year interest rates we can compute the bond price of an 8-year zero coupon bond. So, for example, we can compute the bond price of an 8-year bond at January 1st. Also, we can compute the price of an 8-year bond at February 1st. But we can not compute the price of a "7-year + 11-months" bond at February 1st. This is what we actually would need.

Hence, we need to approximate the bond price whenever the maturity does not match any of the given interest rate maturities. For the "7-year + 11-months" bond price we just assume that the yield curve has the same value as at maturity 8 years, but we use this yield and discount the zero coupon value for only less than the full 8 years.

The following chart visualizes buy and sell prices when rolling over 1-year zero-coupon bonds

In [25]:
int_rates_1yr = int_rates_monthly.loc[:, ['BBK01.WZ3400']]

# compute buy prices
zero_coupon_prices = 1 / (1 + int_rates_1yr/100)

# compute sell prices
zero_coupon_prices_11_month = 1 / (1 + int_rates_1yr/100)**(11/12)

ax = zero_coupon_prices.plot()
zero_coupon_prices_11_month.plot(ax=ax, color='red')
plt.show()

From these sell and buy prices one can derive a 1-year bond index by aggregation. The bond index has lower returns as REXP since it has much smaller duration than REXP:

In [26]:
# compute roll-returns and aggregate
monthly_bond_idx_rets = (zero_coupon_prices_11_month / zero_coupon_prices.shift(1)).dropna()
monthly_bond_idx = monthly_bond_idx_rets.cumprod()

# compare to REXP
rexp_and_synth_1yr = rexp.join(monthly_bond_idx).dropna()
rexp_and_synth_1yr = rexp_and_synth_1yr / rexp_and_synth_1yr.iloc[0, :]

rexp_and_synth_1yr.plot()
plt.show()

Basically the same logic to derive bond indices from interest rates is also implemented in function daily_rolling_bond_index_from_interest_rates. Here the rolling can be done for interest rates of all maturities and rolling can be done on a daily basis in order to get a daily bond index series.

In [27]:
help(int_rate_funcs.daily_rolling_bond_index_from_interest_rates)

Help on function daily_rolling_bond_index_from_interest_rates in module qis_src.int_rate_funcs:

daily_rolling_bond_index_from_interest_rates(int_rates: pandas.core.frame.DataFrame, int_maturity: int, is_pct: bool = True, upsample: bool = False) -> pandas.core.frame.DataFrame
    Compute approximation to rolling bond index for a given maturity.
    
    The approximation is built on several (simplifying) assumptions:
    - rolling over of zero coupon bonds
    - rolling occurs at daily frequency
    - interest rates are simply filled forward for missing days
    - the selling price of the bond is computed with the interest rate prevailing at the 
      full duration, although the bond's duration already did decrease by 1 day.
    - interest rates are interpreted as annual interest rates with annual compounding
    
    Options:
    - is_pct:     Boolean, whether input is percentage interest rates or not
    - upsample:   Boolean, whether resulting bond index should exist on original 
                  interest rate dates only (False), or whether dates should be up-sampled
                  to daily frequency (True)
In [28]:
# get column names and specify respective maturities
int_rates_labels = int_rates_daily.columns
all_maturs = np.array([1, 3, 5, 6, 7, 10])

# variable initialization
all_daily_bond_idxs = None

# compute indices for all maturities
for ii in range(0, len(int_rates_labels)):
    this_int_rate_label = int_rates_labels[ii]
    this_matur = all_maturs[ii]
    
    this_daily_bond_idx = int_rate_funcs.daily_rolling_bond_index_from_interest_rates(int_rates_daily.loc[:, [this_int_rate_label]], this_matur, is_pct=True, upsample=True)
    
    if all_daily_bond_idxs is None:
        all_daily_bond_idxs = this_daily_bond_idx
    else:
        all_daily_bond_idxs = pd.concat([all_daily_bond_idxs, this_daily_bond_idx], axis=1)
